circa 1278","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Great Massingham, Norfolk, England":"Great Massingham, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Great Massingham, Norfolk, Eng.":"Great Massingham, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kimberley, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"Abt 1245–":"about 1245–Deceased","1245–Male":"1245–Deceased","1245–Female":"1245–Deceased","1273–Male":"1273–Deceased","1274–Male":"1274–Deceased","1276–Male":"1276–Deceased","1278–Male":"1278–Deceased","1220–Male":"1220–Deceased","1224–Female":"1224–Deceased","1220":"1220","Abt 1259":"about 1259","1274":"1274","abt. 1276":"about 1276","1273":"1273","1290":"1290","Abt 1273":"about 1273","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","Abt 1245":"about 1245","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","1245":"1245","1244":"1244","1453":"1453","1276":"1276","about 1278":"about 1278","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Great Massingham, Norfolk, England":"Great Massingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Great Massingham, Norfolk, Eng.":"Great Massingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Kimberley, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Woodhouse","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from any of various places (in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Yorkshire, Northumberland, Shropshire, and elsewhere) called Woodhouse, or a topographic name for someone who lived at a ‘house in the wood’ (Middle English <i>wode</i>, <i>hous</i>, Old English <i>wudu</i>, <i>hūs</i>).","variant of   Woodiwiss  , from Middle English <i>wodewose</i>, which by the 16th century was sometimes written as <i>wodowes</i>, <i>woodose</i>, and <i>wodehouse</i>. The confusion with <i>woodhouse</i> probably arose because both words (and both names) were pronounced /wudus/ or /wudǝs/ in local dialect.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Woodis","meanings":["English:","perhaps a nickname from Old English <i>wuduwāsa</i>‘faun, satyr’.","alternatively, a shortened form of   Woodhouse  ."]},{"name":"Woodiwiss","meanings":["English (mainly Derbyshire and Yorkshire): nickname from Middle English <i>wodewose</i>, <i>wodewese</i> (Old English <i>wudewāse</i>) ‘wild man of the woods’. This word was also used to denote a person dressed to represent such a being in a play or pageant. Wodewoses (male and female) were mythical creatures of English and ancient Germanic folklore, akin to the fauns and satyrs of Classical mythology. The surname may also have been acquired by someone who lived and worked in the woods or perhaps by an unusually hairy man."]}]},{"name":"Bertram","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. Ravens were traditional symbols of wisdom in Germanic mythology; Odin was regularly accompanied by ravens called Hugin and Munin. This name was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain.  See also  Bertrand ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":14,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":45,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":70,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by c